{
  "doc_id": "12960",
  "text": "When the flow deviates slightly from local equilibrium in the continuum flow regime, the approximate solution derived from the Boltzmann equation leads to the Navier-Stokes equations [CITATION_1] , where the dissipative terms being proportional to the gradients of velocity and temperature. In terms of NS solution, the shock wave and contact discontinuity are not mathematically discontinuities anymore due to viscous diffusion and heat conductivity. However, in most times the physical thickness of shock wave and contact discontinuity can be much thinner than the mesh size. Therefore, still these waves have to be treated theoretically as discontinuities when solving the Navier-Stokes equations. Once there is discontinuity, the non-equilibrium physics needs to be considered.",
  "correct_citation": {
